body: We are continuously trying to improve documentation, but meanwhile can you please check this [C++ example](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/6a477acecf912f3561349ce43eeb30bafdbebe53/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L1011) and see if you can apply it in Python ?
You may also check https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/how-to/tune-performance.html#iobinding to see if it helps.

Thank you both! Of the 3 sources (the C++ example, the link on the onnxruntime.ai site, and the [IOBinding section of the docs](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/python/inference/api_summary.rst#iobinding)), I found the last one most informative, but thank you for the other links.

If I figure this out on my own, I will open a documentation PR.

issue.title: CPU-inference T5Encoder-XL slower than PyTorch

repository.name: fastT5
repository.description: ⚡ boost inference speed of T5 models by 5x & reduce the model size by 3x.

issue.body:
Hello,

my goal is to convert the T5-XL model with fastT5. To be precise, this model has a model size >2GB and those model types currently seem to not be supported. 
Additionally, I would like to use the T5EncoderModel which consists of only the encoder-part. I have locally adapted some things (removing the decoder part  and using external_data_format) which are unfortunately not really usable for others. 
I would really appreciate it if this could be somehow integrated. 

Going along with the problem with large models, the quantization does not work for large models. For that, an issue https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7974 was already created. 

Now to the actual problem. I am not sure if I made something wrong during my adaption, therefore I would appreciate it if this would be supported. But in the `ort_settings.py` it is documented that 
> default : set this to true, ort will choose the best settings for your hardware. (you can test out different settings for better results.)

Does it really yield the best configuration? In my case, my PyTorch model had a faster inference time. 
I tried to set the default-bool to false to adapt some configurations. But even by setting `n_threads = 2`, I for some reason get a huge memory consumption if infering for a larger number of sequences (>200).

My system:
Intel(R) Xeon(R) Gold 6248 CPU @ 2.50GHz limited to 10 Cores. 
60GB RAM
transformers          4.5.1
tokenizers              0.10.1
onnx                      1.9.0
onnxruntime          1.7.0

The T5EncoderModel-XL is used from huggingface. 

Thank you

issue.title: Remove advice to use IO Binding for this scenario

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Remove a misleading comment in the BERT GPU notebook that suggests using IO Binding, as IO Binding does not show a perf increase for this scenario.

**Motivation and Context**
- This advice is misleading for our users
- We should create a notebook for a scenario where there a perf increase

See #8872

body:
Hi @sam-writer,

We have added some documentation that may help you with this. In this section https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/python/api_summary.html#data-on-device, there is an example of using PyTorch tensors on device.

We have also add a sample for this (currently in PR): https://github.com/natke/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/iobinding-sample/python/api/onnxruntime-python-api.py#L66, showing IO Binding with different PyTorch tensor types.

I tested IO Binding in the notebook you mentioned and it does not show a performance gain in this case (a batch size of 1 and a relative small sequence length). You can see the notebook here: https://github.com/natke/onnxruntime/blob/iobinding-huggingface/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/notebooks/PyTorch_Bert-Squad_OnnxRuntime_GPU.ipynb

We will endeavor to update the notebooks where the benefit is clear.

Thank you for reporting the issue and engaging with ONNX Runtime!
Thank you @natke ! These examples are very helpful.
Awesome @sam-writer! I'll close this issue. Please reach out again if you need more help.
